{"title_page": "Derek Niven", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Derek Niven\n| image = \n| fullname = Derek Dunbar Niven<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11 309\">{{Cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311\n | year = 2010\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 9781845966010\n | page = 309 }}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|12|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Falkirk]], Scotland\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=1}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = Bakewell Town\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]]\n| years1 = 2000\u20132001\n| years2 = 2001\u20132003\n| years3 = 2003\u20132012\n| years4 = 2011\n| years5 = 2012\u20132013\n| years6 = 2013\u20132016\n| years7 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| clubs2 = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| clubs3 = [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] (loan)\n| clubs5 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| clubs6 = [[Buxton F.C.|Buxton]]\n| clubs7 = [[Bakewell Town FC|Bakewell Town]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 297\n| goals3 = 18\n| caps4 = 4\n| goals4 = 0\n| caps5 = 34\n| goals5 = 1\n| caps6 = 54\n| goals6 = 2\n| caps7 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| club-update = 13:56, 20 October 2014 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Derek Dunbar Niven''' (born 12 December 1983) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a midfielder for [[Bakewell Town FC|Bakewell Town.]]\n\nHe has previously played for [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]], [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]], [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]], [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]], [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] and [[Buxton F.C.|Buxton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bolton_wanderers/1681183.stm |title=Bolton snap up Niven |publisher=BBC News |date=28 November 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Raith Rovers===\nHaving begun his career with [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]] as a trainee, he joined [[Scottish Football League]] side [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] in August 2000. He made his debut on 3 February 2001 in a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] in which he came on as a 62nd-minute substitute for [[Kenny Black]]. This would be Niven's only first team appearance for Raith, having also appeared as an unused substitute on numerous occasions.\n\n===Bolton Wanderers===\nOn 18 November 2001 he was signed by [[Sam Allardyce]] for [[Premier League]] newcomers [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on a free transfer. A week later he made his debut for the club's reserve side against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] alongside such players as [[Dean Holdsworth]] and [[Nicky Southall]].<ref>http://www.bwfc.co.uk/page/General/0,,1004~136060,00.html{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He remained a fringe player at the [[Reebok Stadium]] until his departure in December 2003, however during his two-year spell he failed to make a single first team appearance.\n\n===Chesterfield===\nNiven signed for [[Football League Division Two]] side [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] in December 2003, making his debut in English football on 13 December 2003 in a 2\u20132 draw at home to [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]. Niven became a regular in the Spirerites squad and scored his first senior goal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on 24 April 2004. Chesterfield managed to avoid relegation at the end of the 2003\u201304 season having climbed out of the drop zone on the last day of the season at the expense of [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]].\n\nChesterfield were eventually relegated at the end of the 2006\u201307 season, and in November 2008 the club confirmed that Niven had begun treatment for [[testicular cancer]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/nov/24/chesterfield-derek-niven-cancer-treatment |title=Chesterfield's Niven has cancer treatment |work=The Guardian | location=London |date=24 November 2008}}</ref>\nNiven returned to the Chesterfield setup in March 2009 after recovering from a year-long stint suffering with testicular cancer. His return was pronounced with a wonder goal against Grimsby Town on 11 March. In May 2010, Niven struck the decisive goal in a 2\u20131 victory against [[AFC Bournemouth]] at [[Saltergate]], Chesterfield's final game at the stadium before relocation. As Chesterfield's longest serving player at the time, his dramatic [[Volley (football)|volley]] deep into injury time also ensured that he would be the last player to score at Saltergate after 139 years of football at the ground.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tooley |first=Phil |work=The Star (Sheffield) | url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sportheadlines/Some-people-are-on-the.6283205.jp | title=Some people are on the pitch. They think it's all over. It is now... | date=10 May 2010 | accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> This dramatic ending to the 139 years of history was celebrated with an immediate pitch invasion from the home crowd.\n\nHe was released by Chesterfield at the end of the 2011\u201312 season, having made almost 300 league appearances for the club.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.chesterfield-fc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10435~2763923,00.html\n |title       = Spireites issue retained list\n |publisher   = Chesterfield FC\n |date        = 9 May 2012\n |accessdate  = 9 May 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120718024707/http://www.chesterfield-fc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10435~2763923%2C00.html\n |archivedate = 18 July 2012\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>\n\n===Grimsby Town===\nIn July 2012 he began training with [[Conference National]] side [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], alongside former [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] player [[Lewis Chalmers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Grimsby-Town-trialists-Derek-Niven-Lewis-Chalmers/story-16510359-detail/story.html |title=Grimsby Town trialists Derek Niven and Lewis Chalmers aim to shine against Grimsby Borough |publisher=This is Grimsby |date=10 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=Nzd |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> After impressing in the club's 12\u20133 victory over [[Grimsby Borough F.C.|Grimsby Borough]] he was offered a contract by the club, while Chalmers was released.<ref>http://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10417~2848786,00.html{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 16 July 2012 he signed a one-year contract with the club.<ref>http://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10417~2850218,00.html{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Niven was ever present for the club in the centre of midfield with [[Craig Disley]] and helped play a part in the club's promotion and [[FA Trophy]] run in. Grimsby missed out on lifting silverware at [[Wembley Stadium]] having been defeated on penalties to [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]], and later lost out in the play-offs to [[Newport County F.C.|Newport County]]. Town released Niven on 2 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/article/the-retained-list-803613.aspx |title=The Retained List |publisher=Grimsby-townfc.co.uk |date=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Part-time football===\nOn 17 July 2013 it was announced that Niven had dropped a further two leagues down by signing for [[Northern Premier League]] side [[Buxton F.C.|Buxton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/buxtonfc/news/wednesday-round-up-992720.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226152708/http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/buxtonfc/news/wednesday-round-up-992720.html |archivedate=26 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2016, he moved from Buxton FC to join [[Bakewell Town FC]] in the Hope Valley league.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2008 Niven overcame a battle with [[Testicular cancer]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/nov/24/chesterfield-derek-niven-cancer-treatment | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Chesterfield's Niven has cancer treatment | date=24 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;Chesterfield\n*[[Football League 2]] '''Champions (1):'''  [[2010-11 in English football|2010\u201311]]\n*[[Football League Trophy]] '''Winners (1):''' [[2012 Football League Trophy Final|2011\u201312]]\n\n;Grimsby Town\n*[[Lincolnshire Senior Cup]] '''Winners (1):''' [[2012\u201313 in English football|2012\u201313]]\n*[[FA Trophy]] : Runners-up, [[2012-13 in English football|2012\u201313]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Niven, Derek}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Falkirk]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Stenhousemuir F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Raith Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chesterfield F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northampton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Buxton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Testicular cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Derek Niven\n| image = \n| fullname = Derek Dunbar Niven<ref name=\"Hug